<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-cauchy-sequences"
xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Cauchy Sequences</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Sometimes we can show that the terms of a sequence become arbitrarily
      close to one another even before we know what the limit should be. The
      next definition isolates that idea.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    A sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is <term>Cauchy sequence</term><idx>Cauchy
    sequence</idx> if for every <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> there exists
    <m>N\in\N</m> such that <md>
      |x_n-x_m|&lt;\varepsilon \quad\text{whenever } n,m\ge N.
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    In other words, all sufficiently far terms of a Cauchy sequence lie
    close to one another.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-cauchy-one-over-n">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The sequence <m>(1/n)</m> is Cauchy. Indeed, if <m>m,n\ge N</m>, then
        <md>
          \left|\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{m}\right|
          \le \frac{1}{n}+\frac{1}{m}
          \le \frac{2}{N}.
        </md>
        Therefore, once <m>N</m> is large enough that
        <m>2/N&lt;\varepsilon</m>, we have
        <m>|1/n-1/m|&lt;\varepsilon</m> for all <m>m,n\ge N</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="eg-not-cauchy-alternating">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The sequence <m>((-1)^n)</m> is not Cauchy. If <m>n</m> is even, then
        <m>|(-1)^n-(-1)^{n+1}|=2</m>. So no tail of the sequence can have all
        of its terms within distance <m>1</m> of each other.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-convergent-implies-cauchy">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Every convergent sequence is Cauchy.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>x_n\to L</m>. Let <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>. Choose
        <m>N\in\N</m> such that <m>|x_n-L|&lt;\varepsilon/2</m> for all
        <m>n\ge N</m>. Then whenever <m>m,n\ge N</m>, the triangle inequality
        gives
        <md>
          |x_n-x_m|\le |x_n-L|+|x_m-L|&lt; \varepsilon.
        </md>
        Hence <m>(x_n)</m> is Cauchy.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-cauchy-sequence-bounded">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Every Cauchy sequence is bounded.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        Let <m>(x_n)</m> be Cauchy. Then for some <m>N\in\N</m>,
        <m>|x_n-x_m|&lt;1</m> whenever <m>m,n\ge N</m>. In particular,
        for every <m>n\ge N</m>, <md>
          |x_n|\le |x_n-x_N|+|x_N|&lt;1+|x_N|.
	</md> 

	Thus, <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded by
	<m>B:=\max\{|x_1|,\dots,|x_{N-1}|,|x_N|+1\}</m>
      
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    The converse of <xref ref="prop-convergent-implies-cauchy"/> need not hold
    in an arbitrary ordered field.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-sequential-completeness-of-reals">
    <statement>
      <p> <m>\R</m> is sequentially complete <idx><h>sequentially
      complete</h></idx>. That is, every Cauchy sequence of real numbers
      converges.  
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
	A Cauchy sequence <m>(x_n)</m> is bounded (<xref
	ref="prop-cauchy-sequence-bounded"/>) hence, by the Bolzano-Weierstrass
	Theorem (<xref ref="thm-bolzano-weierstrass"/>) admits a convergent
	subsequence <m>(x_{n_k})</m>. Let <m>x_{n_k}\to L</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m>. Since <m>(x_n)</m> is Cauchy, there
        exists <m>N \in\N</m> such that <m>|x_n-x_m|&lt;\varepsilon/2</m>
        whenever <m>m,n\ge N</m>.  Since <m>x_{n_k}\to L</m>, there exists
        <m>K \in\N</m> such that <m>|x_{n_k}-L|&lt;\varepsilon/2</m> for
        every <m>k\ge K</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
	For <m>n,k \ge M:=\max\{N,K\}</m>, because <m>(n_k)</m> is strictly
	increasing, <m>n_k \ge k \ge M \ge N</m>. Thus,
	<md>
	  |x_n-L| \le |x_n-x_{n_k}| + |x_{n_k}-L| &lt;
	  \frac{\varepsilon}{2}+\frac{\varepsilon}{2} = \varepsilon.
	</md>
	This shows that <m>x_n\to L</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <example xml:id="eg-q-not-sequentially-complete">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The ordered field <m>\Q</m> is not sequentially complete. Let
        <m>x_n</m> be the decimal truncation of <m>\sqrt{2}</m> to
        <m>n</m> decimal places. Thus
        <md>
          x_1=1, \qquad x_2=1.4, \qquad x_3=1.41, \qquad x_4=1.414, \dots
        </md>
        Then
        <m>0\le \sqrt{2}-x_n &lt; 10^{-n}</m> for every <m>n</m>. Hence,
        for <m>m,n\ge N</m>,
        <md>
          |x_n-x_m|
          \le |\sqrt{2}-x_n| + |\sqrt{2}-x_m|
          &lt; 2\cdot 10^{-N}.
        </md>
        So <m>(x_n)</m> is Cauchy. But it cannot converge in <m>\Q</m>,
        because as a real sequence it converges to <m>\sqrt{2}</m>, and
        <m>\sqrt{2}\notin\Q</m>. Thus <m>\Q</m> is not sequentially complete.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>

  <p>
    The completeness axiom and sequential completeness do not look alike at
    first. The completeness axiom is a statement about bounded sets, while
    sequential completeness is a statement about Cauchy sequences. The link is
    that one can try to locate the supremum of a nonempty set bounded above by
    repeatedly choosing a point of the set and an upper bound whose distance
    keeps shrinking. This produces Cauchy sequences from below and above, and
    their common limit turns out to be the desired supremum. Thus, for
    <m>\R</m>, the two formulations of completeness are equivalent.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-sequential-completeness-implies-lub">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Sequential completeness of <m>\R</m> implies completeness of
	<m>\R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
	Let <m>A\subseteq \R</m> be non-empty and bounded above. Let
	<m>B</m> be the set of all upper bounds of <m>A</m>. Then <m>B</m>
	is non-empty. Choose <m>a_1\in A</m> and <m>b_1\in B</m>, so in
	particular, <m>a_1 \le b_1</m>.
      </p>

      <p> We will construct, by induction, sequences <m>(a_n)</m> in
      <m>A</m> and <m>(b_n)</m> in <m>B</m> such that
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li> <m>(a_n)</m> is increasing and <m>(b_n)</m> is decreasing.
	</li>
	
	<li> 

	<m> 0 \le b_n-a_n \le \frac{b_1-a_1}{2^{n-1}} </m> for all <m>n \in
	\N</m>. 
	</li>
      
      </ol>
      
      <p>
      Suppose for some <m>k \ge 1</m>, <m>a_i \in A</m> and <m>b_i \in B</m>
      (<m>1 \le i \le k</m>) have been chosen such that
      
      <md number="yes" xml:id='anbn-ind-hyp'>
      a_1 \le a_2 \le \ldots \le a_k \le b_k \le \ldots \le b_2 \le b_1
      </md>
      and <m>b_i - a_i \le (b_1-a_1)/2^{i-1}</m>.

      We choose <m>a_{k+1} \in A</m> and <m>b_{k+1} \in B</m> as follows.
      Let <m>m:=\frac{a_k+b_k}{2}</m>. Then:
      <ol>
        <li><m>m \in B</m>, take <m>b_{k+1} = m</m> and <m>a_{k+1} =a_k</m>.
	</li>
        
	<li>
          If <m>m \notin B</m>, then we choose an element of <m>A</m> that
	  is larger than <m>m</m> to be <m>a_{k+1}</m> and keep
	  <m>b_{k+1}=b_k</m>.
	</li>
      </ol>
      
      In either case, <m>a_k \le a_{k+1} \le b_{k+1} \le b_k</m> and by
      <xref ref='anbn-ind-hyp'/>
      
      <md> b_{k+1} - a_{k+1} \le \frac{1}{2}(b_k - a_k) \le \frac{1}{2^{k}}(b_1
      - a_1).  
      </md>
	So by induction, we have constructed sequences <m>(a_n)</m> in <m>A</m>
	and <m>(b_n)</m> in <m>B</m> with the required properties. 
     </p>
     
     <p> Next, we argue that both sequences are Cauchy. For any <m>n,m</m>
     with <m>n \ge m</m>,
	<m>
	   a_m \le a_n \le b_n \le b_m
	</m>.  Hence,
	
	<md>
	 0 \le |a_n - a_m|, |b_n-b_m| \le b_m - a_m \le \frac{1}{2^{m-1}}(b_1
	 - a_1).
	</md>

	Since <m>(b_1-a_1)/2^{m-1} \to 0</m> as <m>m \to \infty</m>,
	both <m>(a_n)</m> and <m>(b_n)</m> are Cauchy and hence convergent by
	the sequential completeness of <m>\R</m>. Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be
	their limits, respectively. 
     </p>
     
     <p>
     We claim that <m>a=b</m>. Fix any <m>m \in \N</m>, since <m>a_n \le
     b_m</m> for any <m>n</m>, so <m>a \le b_m</m>. Since <m>m</m> is
     arbitrary, we have <m>a \le b</m> and
     
     <md> b-a \le b_n -a_n \le (b_1-a_1)/2^{n-1} </md> for any
     <m>n</m>. Letting <m>n \to \infty</m>, we conclude that <m>a = b</m>. 
    </p>

    <p>
     We now contend that the common limit, say <m>s</m>, of <m>(a_n)</m>
     and <m>(b_n)</m> is the supremum of <m>A</m>. First, <m>s</m> must be
     an upper bound of <m>A</m>. If not, then
      <m>s \lt a_0</m> for some <m>a_0 \in A</m>. But since <m>s</m> is
      the limit of <m>(b_n)</m>, we have <m>b_{n_0} \lt a_0</m> for some
      <m>n_0</m>, contradicting the fact that <m>b_{n_0} \in B</m> is an
      upper bound of <m>A</m>. Next, we argue that any <m>s' \lt s</m> is
      not an upper bound of <m>A</m>.  Otherwise <m>a_n \le s'</m> for each
      <m>n</m> and so <m>a_n \to s \le s'</m>, a contradiction. Putting these
      together shows that <m>s = \sup A</m>, and the proof is complete.  
    </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>
</section>
